<div id="introduction" class="section level1">
<h1>1. INTRODUCTION</h1>
<hr />
<p>Financial fraud is one of the biggest challenges that the financial companies across the globe face. According to report by Nilson Report, credit card frauds resulted in losses amounting to $21.84 billion during 2015. United States accounted for 38.7% of these frauds. (Source: Nilson Report, October 2016). Furthermore, on average, retailers incur $580.5 million in debit card fraud losses and spend $6.47 billion annually on credit and debit card fraud prevention annually (Source: Payments Journal, Feb. 2012).</p>
<p>Fraud can be defined as criminal deception with intent of acquiring financial gain. Over the last two decades, there has been an exponential increase in use of credit cards, particularly in online transactions. As a result the number of credit card frauds has also increased. Identifying fraudulent transactions among millions of transactions every day is extremely difficult. Data scientists around the globe are employing data mining techniques to predict fraudulent transactions. However, it is challenging due to two reasons. First, the profiles of fraudulent and normal behaviors change continuously and second, the fraud datasets are highly skewed (Source: Credit card fraud detection using machine learning techniques: A comparative analysis, John O. Awoyemi ; Adebayo O. Adetunmbi ; Samuel A. Oluwadare).</p>
<p>This project investigates the performance of Gradient Boosting Machine (GBM) using H2O, Support Vector K k-nearest neighbors (KNN) and Random Forest (RF) in predicting the fraud transactions in a highly imbalanced data of credit card transactions in September 2013 by European cardholders. First, detailed Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) was performed on the masked and PCA transformed features. Based on the insights from the EDA, three models were executed which resulted in high performance in predicting the fraud transaction in the test set.</p>
<div id="data-introduction-sourcekaggle" class="section level3">
<h3>DATA INTRODUCTION (SOURCE:KAGGLE)</h3>
<hr />
<p>The dataset contains transactions made by credit cards in September 2013 by European cardholders. This dataset presents transactions that occurred in two days, where we have 492 frauds out of 284,807 transactions. The dataset is highly unbalanced, the positive class (frauds) account for 0.172% of all transactions.</p>
<p>It contains only numerical input variables which are the result of a PCA transformation. Unfortunately, due to confidentiality issues, we cannot provide the original features and more background information about the data. Features V1, V2, … V28 are the principal components obtained with PCA, the only features which have not been transformed with PCA are ‘Time’ and ‘Amount’. Feature ‘Time’ contains the seconds elapsed between each transaction and the first transaction in the dataset. The feature ‘Amount’ is the transaction Amount, this feature can be used for example-dependant cost-senstive learning. Feature ‘Class’ is the response variable and it takes value 1 in case of fraud and 0 otherwise.</p>
</div>
</div>

p3 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">ggplot</span>(<span class="dt">data =</span> data,<span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">x=</span>Time,<span class="dt">fill=</span><span class="kw">factor</span>(Class)))<span class="op">+</span><span class="kw">geom_density</span>(<span class="dt">alpha=</span><span class="fl">0.5</span>)<span class="op">+</span>
<span class="st">  </span><span class="kw">geom_vline</span>(<span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">xintercept=</span><span class="kw">mean</span>(Time[Class<span class="op">==</span><span class="st">&quot;Not Fraud&quot;</span>])),<span class="dt">color=</span><span class="st">&quot;red&quot;</span>,<span class="dt">linetype=</span><span class="st">&quot;dashed&quot;</span>,<span class="dt">lwd=</span><span class="fl">0.5</span>)<span class="op">+</span>
<span class="st">  </span><span class="kw">geom_vline</span>(<span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">xintercept=</span><span class="kw">mean</span>(Time[Class<span class="op">==</span><span class="st">&quot;Fraud&quot;</span>])),<span class="dt">color=</span><span class="st">&quot;blue&quot;</span>,<span class="dt">linetype=</span><span class="st">&quot;dashed&quot;</span>,<span class="dt">lwd=</span><span class="fl">0.5</span>)<span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span>
<span class="st">       </span><span class="kw">scale_x_continuous</span>(<span class="dt">breaks =</span> <span class="kw">seq</span>(<span class="dv">50000</span>,<span class="dv">100000</span>,<span class="dv">150000</span>))<span class="op">+</span>
<span class="st">  </span><span class="kw">xlab</span>(<span class="dt">label =</span> <span class="st">&quot;Time&quot;</span>) <span class="op">+</span>
<span class="st">  </span><span class="kw">ggtitle</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Transaction time of Fraud and Normal transactions&quot;</span>)<span class="op">+</span>
<span class="st">  </span><span class="kw">theme_classic</span>()

<span class="kw">grid.arrange</span>(p3, p1, p2)</code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<ul>
<li>We can clearly see that normal transactions follow a cyclical period. Therefore, if large number of transaction show up in low acitivity period it can raise an alarm</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="exploring-if-fraud-transactions-are-related-with-amount-of-transaction" class="section level4">
<h4>4. Exploring if Fraud Transactions are related with amount of transaction?</h4>
<hr />
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">p3 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">ggplot</span>(fraudData, <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">x =</span> Amount)) <span class="op">+</span>
<span class="st">        </span><span class="kw">geom_histogram</span>(<span class="dt">fill=</span><span class="st">&quot;light blue&quot;</span>, <span class="dt">colour =</span> <span class="st">&quot;black&quot;</span>) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">labs</span>(<span class="dt">title=</span><span class="kw">expression</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Fraud Transactions&quot;</span>))

p4 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">ggplot</span>(notFraudData, <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">x =</span> Amount)) <span class="op">+</span>
<span class="st">        </span><span class="kw">geom_histogram</span>(<span class="dt">fill=</span><span class="st">&quot;light green&quot;</span>, <span class="dt">colour =</span> <span class="st">&quot;black&quot;</span>) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">labs</span>(<span class="dt">title=</span><span class="kw">expression</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Normal Transactions&quot;</span>))

<span class="kw">grid.arrange</span>(p3, p4)</code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<ul>
<li>No particular insights here, most of the transactions appear to be of small amount for both fraud and clean transactions. Lets further look into it by looking at its percentiles</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="cumulative-quintiles-for-fraud-and-normal-transactions" class="section level4">
<h4>Cumulative quintiles for Fraud and Normal transactions</h4>
<hr />
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">##Normal Transactions
<span class="kw">quantile</span>(notFraudData<span class="op">$</span>Amount, <span class="kw">seq</span>(<span class="dv">0</span>, <span class="dv">1</span>, <span class="dt">by=</span>.<span class="dv">2</span>))</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>##       0%      20%      40%      60%      80%     100% 
##     0.00     3.58    13.03    37.00   100.00 25691.16</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">##Fraud Transactions
<span class="kw">quantile</span>(fraudData<span class="op">$</span>Amount, <span class="kw">seq</span>(<span class="dv">0</span>, <span class="dv">1</span>, <span class="dt">by=</span>.<span class="dv">2</span>))</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>##       0%      20%      40%      60%      80%     100% 
##    0.000    1.000    2.000   39.992  152.342 2125.870</code></pre>
<ul>
<li>Clearly 60% of the transactions are of amount less than ~$40. Lets zoom into the transactions under $50 to see if there is an anomaly between fraud and clean transactions</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="cumulative-graphs-for-normal-and-fraud-transaction-amounts" class="section level4">
<h4>Cumulative % graphs for Normal and Fraud transaction amounts</h4>
<hr />
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">tab &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">melt</span>(<span class="kw">table</span>(data<span class="op">$</span>Amount[data<span class="op">$</span>Class<span class="op">==</span><span class="st">'Normal'</span>]))
tab<span class="op">$</span>CummulativePercentage &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">cumsum</span>(tab<span class="op">$</span>value) <span class="op">/</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">sum</span>(tab<span class="op">$</span>value) <span class="co"># cumulative Frequency</span>
<span class="kw">names</span>(tab)[<span class="dv">1</span>] &lt;-<span class="st"> &quot;Amount&quot;</span>
p5 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">ggplot</span>(tab[tab<span class="op">$</span>Amount<span class="op">&lt;</span><span class="dv">50</span>,], <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">x=</span>Amount, <span class="dt">y=</span>CummulativePercentage, <span class="dt">color=</span>CummulativePercentage))<span class="op">+</span>
<span class="st">  </span><span class="kw">geom_line</span>()<span class="op">+</span><span class="kw">ggtitle</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Normal Transactions&quot;</span>)

tab &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">melt</span>(<span class="kw">table</span>(data<span class="op">$</span>Amount[data<span class="op">$</span>Class<span class="op">==</span><span class="st">'Fraud'</span>]))
tab<span class="op">$</span>CummulativePercentage &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">cumsum</span>(tab<span class="op">$</span>value) <span class="op">/</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">sum</span>(tab<span class="op">$</span>value)
<span class="kw">names</span>(tab)[<span class="dv">1</span>] &lt;-<span class="st"> &quot;Amount&quot;</span>
p6 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">ggplot</span>(tab[tab<span class="op">$</span>Amount<span class="op">&lt;</span><span class="dv">50</span>,], <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">x=</span>Amount, <span class="dt">y=</span>CummulativePercentage, <span class="dt">color=</span>CummulativePercentage))<span class="op">+</span>
<span class="st">  </span><span class="kw">geom_line</span>()<span class="op">+</span><span class="kw">ggtitle</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Fraud Transactions&quot;</span>)

<span class="kw">grid.arrange</span>(p5, p6)</code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<ul>
<li>No particular anomoly here. Based on histogram and cummulative frequency above, we can safely say that there is no anomaly based on amount of the transaction</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="exploring-if-fraud-transactions-are-related-with-amount-and-time-of-transaction" class="section level4">
<h4>5. Exploring if Fraud Transactions are related with amount and time of transaction?</h4>
<hr />
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">p7&lt;-<span class="kw">ggplot</span>(fraudData, <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">x=</span>Time, <span class="dt">y=</span>Amount)) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span>
<span class="st">  </span><span class="kw">geom_point</span>(<span class="dt">colour=</span><span class="st">&quot;light blue&quot;</span>) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">ggtitle</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Fraud Transactions&quot;</span>)

p8&lt;-<span class="kw">ggplot</span>(notFraudData, <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">x=</span>Time, <span class="dt">y=</span>Amount)) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span>
<span class="st">  </span><span class="kw">geom_point</span>(<span class="dt">colour=</span><span class="st">&quot;light green&quot;</span>)<span class="op">+</span><span class="kw">ggtitle</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Normal Transactions&quot;</span>)

<span class="kw">grid.arrange</span>(p7, p8)</code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<ul>
<li>Again, no particular anomaly here between fraud and normal transactions.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="which-variables-explain-the-fraud-transactions" class="section level4">
<h4>6. Which variables explain the fraud transactions?</h4>
<hr />
<p><strong>We will use several methods to explore which variables can help in detecting the fraud transaction</strong></p>
<p>First,we need to look at the coorelation of all variablesto find a relation :</p>
<div id="correlation-map" class="section level5">
<h5>Correlation map</h5>
<hr />
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">plot_correlation</span>(data, <span class="dt">maxcat =</span> 8L)</code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<ul>
<li>None of the V1 to V28 PCA components have any correlation to each other.</li>
<li>Little to no correlation between variables indicates that it is highly likely that ** data is pca transformed**</li>
<li>Time has some correlations with V components but not with Amount.</li>
<li>Amount also has some correlations with V components but not with Time.</li>
<li>Class has some positive and negative correlations with the V components but has no significant correlation with Time and Amount.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="comparison-of-mean-of-variables-by-fraud-vs-normal-transactions" class="section level5">
<h5>Comparison of mean of variables by Fraud vs Normal transactions</h5>
<hr />
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">skew &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">sum</span>(<span class="kw">as.numeric</span>(data<span class="op">$</span>Class))<span class="op">/</span><span class="kw">nrow</span>(data)
mugood &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">apply</span>(notFraudData[<span class="kw">sample</span>(<span class="kw">rownames</span>(notFraudData), <span class="dt">size =</span> <span class="kw">as.integer</span>(skew <span class="op">*</span><span class="kw">nrow</span>(data)), <span class="dt">replace =</span> T), <span class="op">-</span><span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">1</span>, <span class="dv">30</span>, <span class="dv">31</span>)], <span class="dv">2</span>, mean)
muanom &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">apply</span>(fraudData[, <span class="op">-</span><span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">1</span>, <span class="dv">30</span>, <span class="dv">31</span>)], <span class="dv">2</span>, mean)
<span class="kw">plot</span>(muanom, <span class="dt">col =</span> <span class="st">&quot;blue&quot;</span>, <span class="dt">xlab =</span> <span class="st">&quot;Features&quot;</span>, <span class="dt">ylab =</span> <span class="st">&quot;Mean&quot;</span>)
<span class="kw">lines</span>(muanom, <span class="dt">col =</span> <span class="st">&quot;blue&quot;</span>, <span class="dt">lwd =</span> <span class="dv">2</span>)
<span class="kw">points</span>(mugood, <span class="dt">col =</span> <span class="st">&quot;green&quot;</span>)
<span class="kw">lines</span>(mugood, <span class="dt">col =</span> <span class="st">&quot;green&quot;</span>, <span class="dt">lwd =</span> <span class="dv">2</span>)
<span class="kw">legend</span>(<span class="st">&quot;topright&quot;</span>, <span class="dt">legend =</span> <span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Normal&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;Fraud&quot;</span>), <span class="dt">lty =</span> <span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">1</span>,<span class="dv">1</span>), <span class="dt">col =</span> <span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="st">&quot;green&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;blue&quot;</span>), <span class="dt">lwd =</span> <span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">2</span>,<span class="dv">2</span>))</code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<ul>
<li>Mean values of variables for fraud transactions are different than for normal transactions for most of the variables.</li>
<li>Mean values for the normal transacitons dont differ.</li>
<li>Mean values for fraud transactions differ alot.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Before we go into the detail of each variable, let’s look at the box plot for all the variables:</strong></p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">boxplot</span>(data[<span class="dv">2</span><span class="op">:</span><span class="dv">29</span>])</code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<ul>
<li>It is worth noticing that V13, V15, V19, and maybe V24 look very symmetrical. We will look at them in detail below</li>
<li>Outliers appear to be a problem. However, outliers also help in detecting anomolies so we will not treat them. Lets look at the correlation map</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="fraud-vs-normal-transactions---deep-diving-into-each-variable" class="section level5">
<h5>Fraud vs Normal Transactions - deep diving into each variable</h5>
<hr />
<p>We will look into each variable to compare its distribution and variance using histogram and boxplots respectively and decide on if we should include the variable in the model</p>
</div>
<div id="v1" class="section level5">
<h5>1. V1</h5>
<hr />
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">p1 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">ggplot</span>(data, <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">x =</span> V1, <span class="dt">fill =</span> Class)) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span>
<span class="st">   </span><span class="kw">geom_histogram</span>(<span class="dt">alpha =</span> <span class="fl">0.5</span>, <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">y =</span> ..density..), <span class="dt">position =</span> <span class="st">'identity'</span>) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">stat_density</span>(<span class="dt">geom =</span> <span class="st">&quot;line&quot;</span>, <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">colour =</span> Class), <span class="dt">adjust =</span> <span class="dv">10</span>) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">xlim</span>(<span class="op">-</span><span class="dv">20</span>,<span class="dv">20</span> ) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">labs</span>(<span class="dt">title=</span><span class="kw">expression</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Distribution&quot;</span>))

p2 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">ggplot</span>(data, <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">y=</span>V1, <span class="dt">x=</span>Class)) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st">  </span><span class="kw">geom_boxplot</span>(<span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">fill =</span> Class)) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">labs</span>(<span class="dt">title=</span><span class="kw">expression</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Box Plot&quot;</span>)) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">xlab</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Type of Transaction&quot;</span>)

<span class="kw">grid.arrange</span>(p1, p2, <span class="dt">top=</span><span class="st">&quot;V1 - Fraud vs Normal Transactions&quot;</span>, <span class="dt">ncol =</span> <span class="dv">2</span>)                                                                                </code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<ul>
<li><p>The distribution of v1 for fraud vs normal transaction have some overlap</p></li>
<li><p>The box plot reflects that the variation is different for fraud vs normal transactions</p></li>
<li><p>Therefore, this variable can be <strong>useful</strong> in predicting fraud</p></li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="v2" class="section level5">
<h5>2. V2</h5>
<hr />
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">p1 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">ggplot</span>(data, <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">x =</span> V2, <span class="dt">fill =</span> Class)) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span>
<span class="st">   </span><span class="kw">geom_histogram</span>(<span class="dt">alpha =</span> <span class="fl">0.5</span>, <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">y =</span> ..density..), <span class="dt">position =</span> <span class="st">'identity'</span>) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">stat_density</span>(<span class="dt">geom =</span> <span class="st">&quot;line&quot;</span>, <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">colour =</span> Class), <span class="dt">adjust =</span> <span class="dv">10</span>) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">xlim</span>(<span class="op">-</span><span class="dv">20</span>,<span class="dv">20</span> ) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">labs</span>(<span class="dt">title=</span><span class="kw">expression</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Distribution&quot;</span>))

p2 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">ggplot</span>(data, <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">y=</span>V2, <span class="dt">x=</span>Class)) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st">  </span><span class="kw">geom_boxplot</span>(<span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">fill =</span> Class)) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">labs</span>(<span class="dt">title=</span><span class="kw">expression</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Box Plot&quot;</span>)) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">xlab</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Type of Transaction&quot;</span>)

<span class="kw">grid.arrange</span>(p1, p2, <span class="dt">top=</span><span class="st">&quot;V2 - Fraud vs Normal Transactions&quot;</span>, <span class="dt">ncol =</span> <span class="dv">2</span>)  </code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<ul>
<li><p>The distribution is very similar and there is a lot of overlap</p></li>
<li><p>The variability in data has some overlap but very similar</p></li>
<li><p>Therefore, this variable <strong>may not be useful</strong> in predicting the fraud</p></li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="v3" class="section level5">
<h5>3. V3</h5>
<hr />
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">p1 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">ggplot</span>(data, <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">x =</span> V3, <span class="dt">fill =</span> Class)) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span>
<span class="st">   </span><span class="kw">geom_histogram</span>(<span class="dt">alpha =</span> <span class="fl">0.5</span>, <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">y =</span> ..density..), <span class="dt">position =</span> <span class="st">'identity'</span>) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">stat_density</span>(<span class="dt">geom =</span> <span class="st">&quot;line&quot;</span>, <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">colour =</span> Class), <span class="dt">adjust =</span> <span class="dv">10</span>) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">xlim</span>(<span class="op">-</span><span class="dv">20</span>,<span class="dv">20</span> ) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">labs</span>(<span class="dt">title=</span><span class="kw">expression</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Distribution&quot;</span>))

p2 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">ggplot</span>(data, <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">y=</span>V3, <span class="dt">x=</span>Class)) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st">  </span><span class="kw">geom_boxplot</span>(<span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">fill =</span> Class)) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">labs</span>(<span class="dt">title=</span><span class="kw">expression</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Box Plot&quot;</span>)) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">xlab</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Type of Transaction&quot;</span>)

<span class="kw">grid.arrange</span>(p1, p2, <span class="dt">top=</span><span class="st">&quot;V3 - Fraud vs Normal Transactions&quot;</span>, <span class="dt">ncol =</span> <span class="dv">2</span>)</code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<ul>
<li><p>The distribution is partially similar</p></li>
<li><p>The variability in data has some overlap but the mean is different</p></li>
<li><p>Therefore, this variable is <strong>useful</strong> in predicting the fraud</p></li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="v4" class="section level5">
<h5>4. V4</h5>
<hr />

<div id="conclusion-of-exploratory-data-analysis" class="section level2">
<h2>7. Conclusion of Exploratory Data Analysis</h2>
<p><strong>Data overview</strong> The dataset has around 285k values with 31 variables, out of which 1 value is missing, and all data are unique. That missing value is one missing transaction time. Three variables are original variables: Class, Time, and Amount. The rest are masked variables due to the sensitive personal information (V1 - V28)</p>
<p><strong>Target Variable Analysis</strong> By plotting the class by the frequency of fraud vs not fraud, we found that this is an unbalanced data with less than 0.2% of fraud transactions.</p>
<p><strong>Transaction Time Analysis</strong> - Transform the Time into day and night we see that most valid transactions take place during the day whereas fraud is more likely to happen than normal transactions during the night. - Analyze the time by class we see that the mean time for valid transaction is larger than that of fraud. - Normal transactions follow a cyclical period. - Therefore, if large number of transaction shows up in low acitivity period it can raise an alarm.</p>
<p><strong>Transaction Amount Analysis</strong> - Most of the transactions appear to be of small amount for both fraud and clean transactions, but fraud transactions have some outliers of large amount - 60% of the transactions are of amount less than ~$40 - No particular anomaly based on amount of the transaction</p>
<p><strong>Amount and Time Analysis</strong> Fit the transaction amount by its time we see that there is also no particular anomoly between fraud and normal transaction. So transaction amount does not have a significant correlation with clean transaction</p>
<p><strong>Blind Data Analysis</strong> The correlation map shows that: - None of the V1 to V28 PCA components have any correlation to each other: it is highly likely that they are already transformed into principle components. - Time has some correlations with V components but not much with Amount. - Amount also has some correlations with V components but not much with Time. - Class has some positive and negative correlations with the V components but has no significant correlation with Time and Amount.</p>
<p>Transformed components are hard to interpret based on instinct, but they are powerful variables in developing our model because selection bias is eliminated. Based on the individual analysis of these variables by target class, these masked variables are divided into following groups: a) Variables that have clearly seperated distribution by class: V4, V11, V12</p>
<ol start="2" style="list-style-type: lower-alpha">
<li><p>Variables that have partially seperated distribution by class: V1, V2, V3, V9, V10</p></li>
<li><p>Variables that have similar mean but with different distributions by class: v5, v6, v7, v8, v14, v16, v17, v18, v19, v20, v21, v22, v23, v27, v28</p></li>
<li><p>Variables that have similar profiles by class V13, V15, V22, V25, V26</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Group a,b,and c could be good predictors in the importance rank of a&gt;b&gt;c. Group d is relatively irrelevant to the target variable.</p>
</div>
</div>

<div id="prepare-model" class="section level5">
<h5>Prepare Model</h5>
<hr />
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">data_gbm &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">h2o.importFile</span>(<span class="st">&quot;creditcard.csv&quot;</span>)</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## 
  |                                                                       
  |                                                                 |   0%
  |                                                                       
  |=================================================================| 100%</code></pre>
<p>Create a list of predictors and change the predicted variable to factor.</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">response &lt;-<span class="st"> &quot;Class&quot;</span>
data_gbm[[response]] &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">as.factor</span>(data_gbm[[response]])
predictors &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">setdiff</span>(<span class="kw">names</span>(data_gbm),response)</code></pre></div>
<p>Split the data into train and test using a ratio of 7:3</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">splits &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">h2o.splitFrame</span>(
  <span class="dt">data =</span> data_gbm, 
  <span class="dt">ratios =</span> <span class="fl">0.7</span>,   
  <span class="dt">seed =</span> <span class="dv">1</span>
)

train_gbm &lt;-<span class="st"> </span>splits[[<span class="dv">1</span>]]
test_gbm &lt;-<span class="st"> </span>splits[[<span class="dv">2</span>]]</code></pre></div>
</div>
<div id="training-model" class="section level5">
<h5>Training Model</h5>
<hr />
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">gbm &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">h2o.gbm</span>(
  ## standard model parameters
  <span class="dt">x =</span> predictors, 
  <span class="dt">y =</span> response, 
  <span class="dt">training_frame =</span> train_gbm, 
  <span class="dt">validation_frame =</span> test_gbm,
  <span class="co">#cross validation using 5 folds</span>
  <span class="dt">nfolds =</span> <span class="dv">5</span>,
  <span class="dt">fold_assignment =</span> <span class="st">&quot;Stratified&quot;</span>,
  <span class="dt">balance_classes =</span> <span class="ot">TRUE</span>,
  <span class="dt">distribution =</span> <span class="st">&quot;bernoulli&quot;</span>,
  ## more trees is better if the learning rate is small enough 
  ## here, we want to use &quot;more than enough&quot; trees as we have early   ## stopping
  <span class="dt">ntrees =</span> <span class="dv">1000</span>,
  ## smaller learning rate is better 
  <span class="dt">learn_rate=</span><span class="fl">0.01</span>,                                                         
  ## early stopping once the validation auc doesn't improve by at least 0.01% for 5 consecutive scoring events
  <span class="dt">stopping_rounds =</span> <span class="dv">5</span>, <span class="dt">stopping_tolerance =</span> <span class="fl">1e-4</span>, <span class="dt">stopping_metric =</span> <span class="st">&quot;AUC&quot;</span>,
  ## sample 80% of rows per tree
  <span class="dt">sample_rate =</span> <span class="fl">0.8</span>,                                              
  ## sample 80% of columns per split
  <span class="dt">col_sample_rate =</span> <span class="fl">0.8</span>,                                           
  ## fix a random number generator seed for reproducibility
  <span class="dt">seed =</span> <span class="dv">1234</span>,                                                      
  ## score every 10 trees to make early stopping reproducible (it depends on the scoring interval)
  <span class="dt">score_tree_interval =</span> <span class="dv">10</span>                                                 
)</code></pre></div>

<div id="random-forest" class="section level3">
<h3>Random Forest</h3>
<hr />
<div id="prepare-model-1" class="section level5">
<h5>Prepare Model</h5>
<hr />
<p>Data spliting: we use the same training and testing set from our first model</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">train&lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">as.data.frame</span>(train_gbm)
<span class="kw">levels</span>(train<span class="op">$</span>Class) &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="st">&quot;NotFraud&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;Fraud&quot;</span>)
test &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">as.data.frame</span>(test_gbm)
<span class="kw">levels</span>(test<span class="op">$</span>Class) &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="st">&quot;NotFraud&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;Fraud&quot;</span>)</code></pre></div>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">basic_rec &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">recipe</span>(Class <span class="op">~</span><span class="st"> </span>.,
                    <span class="dt">data =</span> train) <span class="op">%&gt;%</span>
<span class="st">     </span><span class="co"># remove variables that contain only a single value </span>
<span class="st">     </span><span class="kw">step_zv</span>(<span class="kw">all_predictors</span>()) </code></pre></div>
<p>Rf grid and control</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">ctrl &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">trainControl</span>(
      <span class="co"># use 10-fold CV to resample the data</span>
     <span class="dt">method =</span> <span class="st">&quot;cv&quot;</span>,
     <span class="co">#  compute probabilities for our classification model in each resample</span>
     <span class="dt">classProbs =</span> <span class="ot">TRUE</span>,
     <span class="co"># produce ROC,AUC along with sensitivity and specificity from the default 50% cutoff</span>
     <span class="dt">summaryFunction =</span> twoClassSummary,
     <span class="dt">savePredictions =</span> <span class="st">'final'</span>,
     <span class="co"># downsamping done instide of the resampling</span>
     <span class="dt">sampling =</span> <span class="st">'down'</span>,
     <span class="dt">verboseIter =</span> <span class="ot">FALSE</span>)
rf_grid &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">expand.grid</span>(
    <span class="co"># use the classic squre root of the observation # for number of the # of variables at each split</span>
    <span class="dt">.mtry =</span> <span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">6</span>)
            )</code></pre></div>
<ul>
<li>Because there are imbalances in the class of our data, we might be facing overfitting issues to the majority class. In order to solve this, we down-sample the data to balance the number of “Fraud” and “NotFraud”.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="training-model-1" class="section level5">
<h5>Training Model</h5>
<hr />
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">cl &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">makeCluster</span>(<span class="dv">8</span>)
<span class="kw">registerDoParallel</span>(cl)

rf_mod &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">train</span>(basic_rec,
                 <span class="dt">data =</span> train,
                 <span class="dt">method =</span> <span class="st">'rf'</span>,
                 <span class="dt">metric =</span> <span class="st">&quot;ROC&quot;</span>,
                 <span class="dt">tuneGrid =</span> rf_grid,
                 <span class="dt">trControl =</span> ctrl,
                 <span class="co"># set to grow 500 trees</span>
                 <span class="dt">ntree =</span> <span class="dv">500</span>,
                 <span class="dt">verbose =</span> <span class="ot">FALSE</span>,
                <span class="dt">importance =</span> <span class="ot">TRUE</span>)</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## Loading required namespace: randomForest</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">stopCluster</span>(cl)</code></pre></div>
</div>
<div id="model-performance-analysis-1" class="section level5">
<h5>Model Performance &amp; Analysis</h5>
<hr />
<p>Variable Importance</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">imp &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">varImp</span>(rf_mod, <span class="dt">scale =</span> <span class="ot">FALSE</span>, 
                   <span class="dt">surrogates =</span> <span class="ot">FALSE</span>, 
                   <span class="dt">competes =</span> <span class="ot">FALSE</span>)
imp1 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">ggplot</span>(imp, <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">x=</span><span class="kw">reorder</span>(<span class="kw">rownames</span>(imp)), <span class="dt">y =</span> importance)) <span class="op">+</span>
<span class="st">  </span><span class="kw">geom_bar</span>(<span class="dt">stat=</span><span class="st">&quot;identity&quot;</span>, <span class="dt">fill=</span><span class="st">&quot;lightblue&quot;</span>, <span class="dt">colour=</span><span class="st">&quot;black&quot;</span>) <span class="op">+</span>
<span class="st">  </span><span class="kw">coord_flip</span>() <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span>
<span class="st">  </span><span class="kw">labs</span>(<span class="dt">title=</span><span class="st">&quot;Prediction using RandomForest&quot;</span>, <span class="dt">x=</span><span class="st">&quot;Variable&quot;</span>, <span class="dt">y=</span><span class="st">&quot;Variable importance&quot;</span>)</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## Coordinate system already present. Adding new coordinate system, which will replace the existing one.</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">imp1</code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<ul>
<li>Again, similar to GBM, V10, V14 and V4 are the most important variables in the random forest model. Interestingly, time, which we believed to be important in the EDA, does not rank high in the variable importance.</li>
</ul>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">draw_confusion_matrix &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="cf">function</span>(test, title) {
    tst &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">data.frame</span>(test<span class="op">$</span>predicted, test<span class="op">$</span>Class)
    opts &lt;-<span class="st">  </span><span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Prediction&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;True&quot;</span>)
    <span class="kw">names</span>(tst) &lt;-<span class="st"> </span>opts
    cf &lt;-<span class="st"> </span>plyr<span class="op">::</span><span class="kw">count</span>(tst)
    cf[opts][cf[opts]<span class="op">==</span><span class="dv">0</span>] &lt;-<span class="st"> &quot;Not Fraud&quot;</span>
    cf[opts][cf[opts]<span class="op">==</span><span class="dv">1</span>] &lt;-<span class="st"> &quot;Fraud&quot;</span>
    
    <span class="kw">ggplot</span>(<span class="dt">data =</span>  cf, <span class="dt">mapping =</span> <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">x =</span> True, <span class="dt">y =</span> Prediction)) <span class="op">+</span>
<span class="st">      </span><span class="kw">labs</span>(<span class="dt">title =</span> <span class="st">&quot;Confusion Matrix&quot;</span>, <span class="dt">subtitle =</span> title) <span class="op">+</span>
<span class="st">      </span><span class="kw">geom_tile</span>(<span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">fill =</span> freq), <span class="dt">colour =</span> <span class="st">&quot;black&quot;</span>) <span class="op">+</span>
<span class="st">      </span><span class="kw">geom_text</span>(<span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">label =</span> <span class="kw">sprintf</span>(<span class="st">&quot;%1.0f&quot;</span>, freq)), <span class="dt">vjust =</span> <span class="dv">1</span>) <span class="op">+</span>
<span class="st">      </span><span class="kw">scale_fill_gradient</span>(<span class="dt">low =</span> <span class="st">&quot;lightgreen&quot;</span>, <span class="dt">high =</span> <span class="st">&quot;green&quot;</span>) <span class="op">+</span>
<span class="st">      </span><span class="kw">theme_bw</span>() <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">theme</span>(<span class="dt">legend.position =</span> <span class="st">&quot;none&quot;</span>)}</code></pre></div>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">test<span class="op">$</span>predicted &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">predict</span>(rf_mod ,test)
<span class="kw">confusionMatrix</span>(rf_mod)</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## Cross-Validated (10 fold) Confusion Matrix 
## 
## (entries are percentual average cell counts across resamples)
##  
##           Reference
## Prediction NotFraud Fraud
##   NotFraud     97.0   0.0
##   Fraud         2.8   0.2
##                             
##  Accuracy (average) : 0.9715</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">draw_confusion_matrix</span>(test,<span class="st">&quot;Random Forest&quot;</span>)</code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<ul>
<li>Based on the results, our model produces an accuracy of 0.97, and a sensitivity of 0.79. Now let’s focus on sensitivity (false positives and false negatives) and look at ROC/AUC next.</li>
</ul>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">print</span>(rf_mod)</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## Random Forest 
## 
## 199614 samples
##     30 predictor
##      2 classes: 'NotFraud', 'Fraud' 
## 
## Recipe steps: zv 
## Resampling: Cross-Validated (10 fold) 
## Summary of sample sizes: 179652, 179652, 179653, 179653, 179652, 179653, ... 
## Addtional sampling using down-sampling
## 
## Resampling results:
## 
##   ROC        Sens       Spec     
##   0.9824811  0.9716252  0.9092857
## 
## Tuning parameter 'mtry' was held constant at a value of 6</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">plot_roc &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="cf">function</span>(x, ...) {
  roc_obj &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">roc</span>(
    <span class="dt">response =</span> x[[<span class="st">&quot;obs&quot;</span>]], 
    <span class="dt">predictor =</span> x[[<span class="st">&quot;Fraud&quot;</span>]], 
    <span class="dt">levels =</span> <span class="kw">rev</span>(<span class="kw">levels</span>(x<span class="op">$</span>obs))
  )
  <span class="kw">plot</span>(roc_obj, ...)
  <span class="kw">matplot</span>(<span class="kw">data.frame</span>(roc_obj<span class="op">$</span>sensitivities, roc_obj<span class="op">$</span>specificities), <span class="dt">x =</span> roc_obj<span class="op">$</span>thresholds, 
      <span class="dt">type=</span><span class="st">'l'</span>, 
  <span class="dt">xlab =</span> <span class="st">'threshold'</span>, <span class="dt">ylab=</span><span class="st">'TPR, TNR'</span>)
  <span class="kw">legend</span>(<span class="st">'bottomright'</span>, <span class="dt">legend=</span><span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="st">'TPR'</span>, <span class="st">'TNR'</span>))
   <span class="co"># include the area under curve</span>
  <span class="kw">return</span>(<span class="kw">auc</span>(roc_obj))
  }</code></pre></div>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">plot_roc</span>(rf_mod<span class="op">$</span>pred,<span class="dt">col =</span> <span class="st">&quot;lightblue&quot;</span>)</code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<pre><code>## Area under the curve: 0.9815</code></pre>
<ul>
<li>Conclusion: Though the model produces a great accuracy, the accuracy calculated in our model may not be as meaningful due to the imbalances in our class. We see that threshhold around 0.3 is where TPR equals TNR, and we get a good AUC of 0.982.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div id="knn" class="section level3">
<h3>KNN</h3>
<hr />
<p>We believe the tree models will work great with the imbalanced data set. Just a curiosity, we predicted using a non-tree model - knn and compared the results as below.</p>
<div id="prepare-model-2" class="section level5">
<h5>Prepare Model</h5>
<hr />
<ul>
<li>Due to imbalances, this time we use both downsampling and upsampling technique to get a raletively balanced data set.</li>
</ul>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">data_both &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">ovun.sample</span>(Class <span class="op">~</span><span class="st"> </span>., <span class="dt">data =</span> train, <span class="dt">method =</span> <span class="st">&quot;both&quot;</span>, <span class="dt">p=</span><span class="fl">0.5</span>, <span class="dt">N=</span><span class="dv">10000</span>, <span class="dt">seed =</span> <span class="dv">123</span>)<span class="op">$</span>data
<span class="kw">table</span>(data_both<span class="op">$</span>Class)</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## 
## NotFraud    Fraud 
##     5057     4943</code></pre>
<p>As you can see, the data after sampling is much more balanced.</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="co">#Run KNN Model for Data Set</span>
cl &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">makeCluster</span>(<span class="dv">8</span>)
<span class="kw">registerDoParallel</span>(cl)
control &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">trainControl</span>(<span class="dt">method=</span><span class="st">&quot;repeatedcv&quot;</span>, <span class="dt">number=</span><span class="dv">10</span>, <span class="dt">repeats=</span><span class="dv">3</span>, <span class="dt">savePredictions=</span><span class="ot">TRUE</span>, <span class="dt">classProbs=</span><span class="ot">TRUE</span>)
<span class="kw">set.seed</span>(<span class="dv">222</span>)
knn_both_mod &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">train</span>(Class<span class="op">~</span>., <span class="dt">data=</span>data_both, <span class="dt">trControl=</span>control, <span class="dt">method =</span> <span class="st">&quot;knn&quot;</span>)

<span class="kw">stopCluster</span>(cl)</code></pre></div>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="co">#Predict Model on Test Set</span>
pred_both &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">predict</span>(knn_both_mod, <span class="dt">newdata =</span> test)</code></pre></div>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="co">#Evaluate the Model by Looking at the ConfusionMatrix</span>
<span class="kw">confusionMatrix</span>(test<span class="op">$</span>Class, pred_both, <span class="dt">positive =</span> <span class="st">&quot;Fraud&quot;</span>)</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## Confusion Matrix and Statistics
## 
##           Reference
## Prediction NotFraud Fraud
##   NotFraud    68856 16198
##   Fraud          65    74
##                                           
##                Accuracy : 0.8091          
##                  95% CI : (0.8064, 0.8117)
##     No Information Rate : 0.809           
##     P-Value [Acc &gt; NIR] : 0.4708          
##                                           
##                   Kappa : 0.0058          
##  Mcnemar's Test P-Value : &lt;2e-16          
##                                           
##             Sensitivity : 0.0045477       
##             Specificity : 0.9990569       
##          Pos Pred Value : 0.5323741       
##          Neg Pred Value : 0.8095563       
##              Prevalence : 0.1910016       
##          Detection Rate : 0.0008686       
##    Detection Prevalence : 0.0016316       
##       Balanced Accuracy : 0.5018023       
##                                           
##        'Positive' Class : Fraud           
## </code></pre>
<ul>
<li>As expected, the knn model did not do well predicting on the test set due to the highly imbalanced nature of the data set. Many data points will automatically be classified as non-fraudulent due to the large volume of non-fraudulent neightbors. Therefore, we exclude this model from our predictions on the data set, and compare only the gbm and random forest models.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="model-comparison-conclusion" class="section level2">
<h2>Model Comparison &amp; Conclusion</h2>
<hr />
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">gbm_pred_df &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">cbind</span>(test,pred)

gbm_pred_df &lt;-<span class="st"> </span>gbm_pred_df <span class="op">%&gt;%</span><span class="st"> </span>
<span class="st">  </span><span class="kw">mutate</span>(<span class="dt">fraud =</span> <span class="kw">if_else</span>(predict <span class="op">==</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">0</span>, <span class="dv">1</span><span class="op">-</span>p0, p0))

<span class="kw">plot</span>(<span class="kw">roc</span>(rf_mod<span class="op">$</span>pred<span class="op">$</span>obs, rf_mod<span class="op">$</span>pred<span class="op">$</span>Fraud, <span class="dt">thresholds =</span> <span class="fl">0.3</span>), <span class="dt">col =</span> <span class="st">'blue'</span>)
<span class="kw">plot</span>(<span class="kw">roc</span>(gbm_pred_df<span class="op">$</span>Class, gbm_pred_df<span class="op">$</span>fraud), <span class="dt">add =</span> <span class="ot">TRUE</span>, <span class="dt">col =</span> <span class="st">'orange'</span>)</code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<p>A couple observations from the model analysis and comparisons: * Tree models work better on imbalanced data set * Both GBM and random forest show great performance in predicting frauds (high sensitivity) * Random forest is slightly better than GBM due to a higher AUC; GBM is slightly better due to a higher sensitivity rate. As a conclusion, we recommend to use the GBM model as we want to be cautious in predicting fraudulent transactions.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="conclusion" class="section level1">
<h1>4.Conclusion</h1>
<hr />
<p>In this project we have used three machine learning models to predict fraudulent transactions on a highly imbalanced data of credit card transactions in September 2013 by European cardholders. The results were very promising for tree-based models i.e. Random Forest and Gradient Boosting (with H2O). Random forest had an AUC value of 98.2% while GBM had an AUC value of 97.3%</p>
<p>Based on our analysis, we found that these algorithms performed better because they were able to balance the class variable effectively. Moreover, number of features can be reduced using the Principal Component Analysis concept to improve the running time of the classification algorithm.</p>
<p>We noted that the choosing the right balance between sensitivity, specificity and accuracy is pivotal for an imbalance data like credit card fraud logs. Usually it is desirable to have higher accuracy and sensitivity for prediction but our rigorous data engineering revealed that for financial data like credit card fraud logs, it makes more sense to aim for higher sensitivity for accurate prediction of fraudulent transactions.</p>
</div>
